<br>
Basically the superstiotion goes that if u try to ride a horse through the cemetery at night then it will become spooked, jump and knock its rider off then bolt....why?<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/emoticons_classic/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ....it is believed that horses can see the dead walking in the cemetery.<br>
<br>
How do i know this? well, I have polish relatives and have been to visit quite a lot, my grandmother owns a summer house in the countryside, quite a desolate little place but don't have this image of an &quot;18th century&quot; village. Anyway, for a small seemingly uninteresting village it has quite a history...i'll post some more FACTS in the future, but for now: horses.<br>
<br>
The Grandfather of a good friend of mine once told us of the horse superstition, of course we didn't believe him but he told us that when he was a kid (some time in the 30's) he and his friends were also told of this tale and like us thought it was all nonsence. One night they decided to take one of their horses (in those days everybody had a horse) and take it to the nearest cemetery which was situated some 4 miles out of town, my friends grandfather seemed to be the bravest of the bunch and so he volunteered to ride through the cemetery. As he got on the horse and approcahed the main gate the horse evidentally became edgy and as they drew closer the horse was in obvious panic, so much so that it jumped up, throwing its rider off and bolting. All of the men took fright and ran all the way back home, in the night through forested areas.<br>
<br>
After this we were quite confused, because the old man seemed to be telling the truth, he's been a good friend to my family for a long time, in fact my grandfather was also one of the men who went that night. All those who were there we asked, bringing it up in general conversation and they all seamed deadly serious about what had happend. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :? --><img src=http://web.ukonline.co.uk/unexplained.m/smile/ponder.gif ALT=":?"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
